• Understanding factors that influence interkey intervals requires a theory of how keystrokes are sequenced.
  • Which processes are required and how are they coordinated?

Serial view

  • Interkey intervals are longer at larger linguistic edges following relatively fluent production bursts (Chenoweth and Hayes 2001; Hayes 2012; Kaufer, Hayes, and Flower 1986).
  • Mean pause duration before a writer starts a sentence is typically longer than before a mid-sentence word and these are, in turn, longer than between mid-word key presses (e.g. Conijn, Roeser, and van Zaanen 2019).
  • Planning message and syntax for the next sentence adds to the time required to prepare the upcoming word, and the motor planning required to produce the first keystroke (Baaijen, Galbraith, and De Glopper 2012; Roeser, Torrance, and Baguley 2019).

Parallel view

  • Writers often do not hesitate before sentence (or word) onset.
  • In some cases sentences are not planned, planning was postponed until after sentence onset, or planning was completed in parallel with previous output [Nottbusch (2010); dam09; Roeser, Torrance, and Baguley (2019)].
  • Sentence initial durations are often shorter than what one would expect if sentence-initial pauses reflect planning.
    • Medimorec and Risko (2017): 71% of sentence-initial interkey intervals shorter than 1 sec. 
    • Rønneberg et al. (2022): 50% sentence-initial intervals were around 430 msecs but 1.2 secs for the remainder.
  • Fluent output is maintained by a cascade of processes that run in parallel (Olive 2014; Van Galen 1991).

Two distinct data-generating processes leading to a mixture of two distributions of interkey intervals (Roeser et al. 2021).

  • Minimum interkey intervals for executing motor movements; 100-150 msecs (Conijn, Roeser, and van Zaanen 2019; Van Waes et al. 2021).
  • If upstream processes provide output more slowly, then interkey intervals are determined by time taken to complete upstream processes and not on finger movement.
  • Neither process (or distribution of keystrokes) can be explained on the basis of the keystroke location in the text.

Model overview

Models Description
Serial
M1 Single distribution Gaussian
M2 Single distribution log-Gaussian
M3 Single distribution log-Gaussian with different variance components per text location
Parallel
M4 Two-distributions mixture of log-Gaussians.

Implentation

  • Bayesian inference (e.g. Lambert 2018)
  • Random effects for participants (see Roeser et al. 2021) with code based on Vasishth et al. (2017)
  • Stan (Carpenter et al. 2016) using rstan (Stan Development Team 2018) to interface with \(R\)
  • Leave-one-out cross-validation estimated as the sum of the expected log predictive density \(\widehat{elpd}\) and compared by the difference between models \(\Delta\widehat{elpd}\) (Vehtari, Gelman, and Gabry 2015, 2017)
  • Difference between models was summarised as \(\mid\frac{\Delta\widehat{elpd}}{\text{SE}}\mid\), the z-score of the difference between models (Sivula et al. 2020).

Planning text unfolds in parallel to production!

Planning text unfolds in parallel to production!

  • Writers do not necessarily pause but plan utterances in parallel to writing.
  • Evidenced by
    • stronger predictive performance of mixture models (Roeser et al. 2021).
    • pauses are generally equally likely before before sentences compare to before words (but often longer).
  • Largely consistent for populations with different levels of writing experience, languages (e.g. young / L2 writers, students), composition tasks.
  • First robust evidence that written composition is largely a parallel process.

“Maybe mixture models just always fit bettter?”

Simulation



  • Simulate data from a single log-normal distribution
  • Simulate data from a mixture of to log-normal distribution
  • Data simulated with mixture process:
    • Advantage for mixture model over single process model: \(\Delta\widehat{elpd} =\) -191.3 (16.5)
  • Data simulated with single process:
    • Negligible difference between models: \(\Delta\widehat{elpd} =\) -0.5 (0.7)
